Taiwan's economy started the year poorly - ECNS
Xinhua News Agency, Taipei, February 11 (Reporters Zhao Bo and Huang Yang) Export trade volume "even five black", manufacturing Purchasing Managers' Index (PMI) contracted for seven consecutive months, consumer price index (CPI) also saw "three prefixes" ... Recently, Taiwan authorities have released economic data for January 2023.
Expert analysis believes that Taiwan's economy began the year with poor performance, growth pressure is not small.
Taiwan's exports fell 21.2 percent to $31.51 billion in January, the fifth consecutive month of negative growth, according to the Taiwan authorities' financial affairs department.
Exports of 11 major export categories declined compared with the same period last year.
Plastics and rubber products and optical equipment fell the most, by 37.6% and 35.7% respectively.
Exports of electronic components fell 20.1% year-on-year, the largest decline in 11 years.
Among them, integrated circuits fell 18.3% year-on-year, the biggest decline in 14 years.
Cai Mena, director of the department's statistics department, said that this shows the spread of weak demand in the consumer electronics industry, the electronics industry has entered a period of correction.
Statistics show that Taiwan's imports and exports fell in January, with an excess of only $2.34 billion, the lowest level in nearly three years.
The financial affairs department of the Taiwan authorities believes that the decline in global terminal demand, industrial adjustment of inventories to curb the willingness of manufacturers to buy materials, export decline is unlikely to improve in the short term, Taiwan's export recession in the first quarter of this year is likely to be higher than expected.
Taiwan's manufacturing Purchasing Managers' Index (PMI) stood at a seasonally adjusted 40.4 per cent in January, down 3.3 percentage points from December and tightening for the seventh consecutive month, according to Taiwan's China Economic Research Institute.
In the system of economic monitoring indicators, the PMI takes 50% as the boom-bust line, and an index greater than 50% represents economic expansion, while the opposite is contraction.
Among the five components of Taiwan's PMI in January, new orders, production and labor hiring contracted, supplier delivery times fell, and inventories tightened.
All six major industries reported a contraction in the PMI, with the power and mechanical equipment industry (35.1%), the electronics and optics industry (35.2%), the chemical and biomedical industry (39.2%), the basic raw materials industry (42.4%), the transportation industry (42.6%) and the food and textile industry (45.7%).
On the price front, Taiwan's Comptroller General's Office announced that Taiwan's CPI increased at an annual rate of 3.04 percent in January this year, breaking through 3 percent again since July last year.
Among them, vegetable prices soared 28.25 per cent to a 17-month high.
Cao Zhihong, a special member of Taiwan's Comptroller General Office, said frankly that the increase in vegetable prices did exceed expectations. Excluding the Spring Festival factor, the average CPI in January and February this year should be close to 2.71 percent in December last year.
Looking ahead to Taiwan's economy this year, experts expressed pessimism based on media reports from the island such as Yonhap News and Yahoo Finance.
Wu Daren, a professor at the Department of Economics of Central University in Taiwan, analyzed that the export recession may cause cash flow problems for export manufacturers and increase the risk of debt default.
At the same time, the decline in orders led manufacturers to cut labor costs, affecting the labor market and the household economy, which in turn affected consumption capacity.
Qiu Dasheng, a researcher at the Taiwan Institute of Economic Research, believes that the inflation situation in Europe and the United States is unresolved this year, demand continues to shrink, and predicts that Taiwan's export recession will continue into the first half of the year.
As Taiwan's economy is supported by exports, the full-year economic growth performance will be weaker than last year due to the impact of the export downturn.
