Singapore's tourism industry recovers strongly, with arrivals 19 times higher than in 2021
The Singapore Tourism Board (STB) recently announced that the number of international tourists visiting Singapore in 2023 is expected to reach 12 million to 14 million, which will bring about S$18 billion to S$21 billion in tourism revenue.
The Singapore tourism market will gradually restart and recover in 2022.
According to the latest statistics released by the Singapore Tourism Board, tourist arrivals in 2022 increased 19-fold to 6.3 million from 330,600 in 2021, surpassing the board's earlier estimate of 4 million to 6 million, and tourists have recovered to 33% of pre-pandemic levels.
From January to September 2022, Singapore's tourism revenue totalled S$8.96 billion, and is expected to reach S$13.8 billion to S$14.3 billion in 2022, a six- to seven-fold increase from S$1.89 billion in 2021, and has recovered to about 50 to 52 per cent of pre-2019 levels.
The Singapore government has taken multiple measures to accelerate the recovery of the tourism industry.
In April 2022, the government announced nearly S$500 million to stimulate tourism recovery.
The Tourism Board has announced plans to allocate S$110 million from this budget over the next two years to launch more business and leisure activities to attract visitors back.
To make health and wellness one of Singapore's tourism highlights, the Singapore Tourism Board (STB) launched a call for expressions of interest on 23 November 2022 to develop a health and wellness attraction on Singapore's south coast.
'In recent years, more and more tourists have put their health at the top of their list of considerations,' said Wang Ling-li, executive director of sports and wellness tourism at the Singapore Tourism Board.
The development of a health and wellness attraction in the Marina South area, which is home to Gardens by the Bay and Marina Barrage, is expected to contribute to Singapore's tourism industry and economy, allowing visitors to spend and stay longer in Singapore.
Health and wellness will become an important part of Singapore's tourism product in the next few years, said Tan Kin Lung, director of the Singapore Tourism Board.
It has raised public awareness and demand for physical and mental health.
To this end, the Tourism Bureau has been promoting health and wellness programmes to the local public and international tourists for the past two years.
In June 2022, the Singapore Tourism Board held its first Health and Wellness Festival, offering more than 130 health activities and experiences to the public.
Singapore will continue to offer visitors new travel experiences.
In addition to the newly opened Singapore Children's Museum, Avatar World at Gardens by the Bay, Sentosa Central Beach Bazaar, the new "Explore New Frontiers" exhibition hall at the Museum of Arts and Sciences, and the new amphitheatre at the Night Safari, the Tourism Board will support the development and renewal of projects such as the Bird Park at Wild Animal World to make Singapore an attractive international destination.
According to the plan, Singapore will develop industry standards for the sustainable development of MICE tourism by 2023, with a focus on improving waste disposal and carbon emissions to further optimize the tourism environment.
The recovery of Singapore's tourism industry has accelerated the recovery of the airline industry.
Data show that as of December 18, 2022, Changi Airport has experienced a strong recovery in passenger traffic, receiving as many as 150,000 passengers per day and about 1 million passengers per week, equivalent to about 75% of the pre-pandemic level, and the number of employees in the aviation industry has returned to about 90% of the pre-pandemic level.
Data show that from January to October 2022, Singapore has received 23.6 million passengers, equivalent to 42% of the pre-pandemic level, and 170,000 flights, 53% of the pre-pandemic level.
The rapid recovery of the tourism industry has also led to the pace of recovery in the accommodation, transportation, dining and shopping industries.
The Singapore government and tourism industry have high hopes for the Chinese market.
Ke Shudan, assistant director of the international division of the Singapore Tourism Board, said a survey by a Chinese travel platform showed that Singapore ranked among the top three in the world in terms of safety, which is one of the reasons why Singapore is so popular with Chinese tourists.
Before COVID-19, about 3.6 million people from China traveled to Singapore for vacation every year.
As China relaxes its border policies, the number of Chinese tourists this year is expected to return to 30% to 60% of 2019.
Ke Shudan pointed out that next, the tourism bureau will pay close attention to further signals from China's outbound travel policy to respond to changes in tourist demand.
In addition to strengthening partnerships with Chinese online travel platforms and travel agencies such as Ctrip, the Singapore Tourism Board will actively prepare to receive Chinese tourists in response to new trends in overseas travel from China.
Looking ahead to the tourism market in 2023, the Singapore Tourism Board is confident that the tourism industry will recover faster than expected as long as there is no significant downturn in the global economy affecting public revenues and no new large-scale deadly outbreaks.
